DOCUMENT();
############################################################ # Load Macros ############################################################ loadMacros( "PGstandard.pl", "PGML.pl", "AnswerFormatHelp.pl", "PGlateximage.pl", "scaffold.pl", "parserNumberWithUnits.pl", "Pd.pl", "PGcourse.pl", ); COMMENT('Authored in PreTeXt'); COMMENT('This problem is scaffolded with multiple parts');
############################################################ # Header ############################################################ TEXT(beginproblem());
############################################################ # PG Setup Code ############################################################ Context('Numeric'); $newUnits = [ {name=>'feet',conversion=>{factor=>12*2.54/100,m=>1}}, {name=>'foot',conversion=>{factor=>12*2.54/100,m=>1}}, {name=>'ft',conversion=>{factor=>12*2.54/100,m=>1}}, {name=>'hour',conversion=>{factor=>60*60,s=>1}}, {name=>'hours',conversion=>{factor=>60*60,s=>1}}, {name=>'hr',conversion=>{factor=>60*60,s=>1}}, {name=>'hrs',conversion=>{factor=>60*60,s=>1}}, {name=>'h',conversion=>{factor=>60*60,s=>1}}, ]; @s=( NumberWithUnits("500 ft/h",{newUnit=>$newUnits}), NumberWithUnits("0 ft/h",{newUnit=>$newUnits}), NumberWithUnits("-875 ft/h",{newUnit=>$newUnits}) );
$image_1 = createLaTeXImage(); $image_1->addToPreamble(latexImagePreamble()); $image_1->BEGIN_LATEX_IMAGE \begin{tikzpicture} \begin{axis}[ xlabel={time (h)}, ylabel={elevation (ft)}, xmin=0, xmax=26, ymin=0, ymax=4000, minor xtick={0,...,25}, xtick=, ytick={0,500,...,3500}, minor ytick=, width=0.47\orccaprintwidth, axis line style={->}, ] \addplot[firstcurve,-] coordinates {(0,0) (7,3500) (19,3500) (23,0)}; \end{axis} \end{tikzpicture}
END_LATEX_IMAGE
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Kato is training for a race up the slope of Mt.[$NBSP]*Hood, from Sandy to Government Camp, and then back. The graph models his elevation from his starting point as time passes. Find the slopes of the three line segments and interpret their meanings in this context.
>> [@image(insertGraph($image_1), width=>282)@]* <<
END_PGML
############################################################ # Scaffold ############################################################ Scaffold::Begin(numbered => 1,is_open => "correct_or_first_incorrect",can_open => always,);
############################################################ # Section ############################################################ Section::Begin("");
BEGIN_PGML What is the slope of the first segment?
[_]{$s[0]}{10}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION The first segment started at [`(0,0)`] and stopped at [`(7,3500)\text{.}`] This implies Kato started at the starting point, traveled [`7`] hours and reached a point [`3500`] feet higher in elevation from the starting point. The slope of the line is
[``` \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{3500\,\text{ft}}{7\,\text{h}}=500\,\frac{\text{ft}}{\text{h}} ```]
In context, Kato was gaining [`500`] feet in elevation per hour.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
Section::End();
############################################################ # Section ############################################################ Section::Begin("");
BEGIN_PGML What is the slope of the second segment?
[_]{$s[1]}{10}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION What happened in the second segment, which started at [`(7,3500)`] and ended at [`(19,3500)\text{?}`] This implies he started this portion [`3500`] feet high, and didn't change elevation for [`19`] hours. Maybe some of that time he was running at a constant elevation, and some of that time he was resting.
[``` \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{0\,\text{ft}}{12\,\text{h}}=0\,\frac{\text{ft}}{\text{h}} ```]
In context, Kato was running but neither gaining nor losing elevation.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
Section::End();
############################################################ # Section ############################################################ Section::Begin("");
BEGIN_PGML What is the slope of the third segment?
[_]{$s[2]}{10}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION The third segment started at [`(19,3500)`] and stopped at [`(23,0)\text{.}`] This implies Kato started this part of his trip from [`3500`] feet high, traveled for [`4`] hours, and returned to the starting elevation. The slope of the line is
[``` \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{-3500\,\text{ft}}{4\,\text{h}}=-875\,\frac{\text{ft}}{\text{h}} ```]
In context, Kato was dropping in elevation by [`875`] feet per hour.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
